}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 115-117.}{\plain \fs24   The author's apostrophe of the emperor Constantine (reigned 306-337) holds him \softline
responsible for the so-called 'Donation of Constantine,' by which he granted temporal sovereignty \softline
to Pope Sylvester I (314-335) -- and his successors -- over Italy and the rest of the western empire.  
This document was considered genuine until Lorenzo Valla, in the fifteenth century, demonstrated \softline
that it was a forgery.  For Dante it was genuine and a cause for excited concern.  (His views on the \softline
subject are exposited forcefully in the later }{\plain \fs24 \i Monarchia}{\plain \fs24  [III.x.1-9]).  In his view the emperor was \softline
not empowered to give over his authority; thus the document was truthful, but its legitimacy \softline
compromised.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab We are perhaps meant to understand by these lines that Sylvester, who cured Constantine of \softline
leprosy and was, as a result, rewarded by him with authority over the Roman empire, is the bottom-most pope in this hole, the 'first rich Father,' a condition that was to his immediate benefit but to the \softline
eventual loss of all Christians.\par
